ac{1}{y^3}\\frac{dy}{dx}$$ and $$\\frac{1}{y^2}$$ into $$\\frac{1}{y^3}\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{1}{xy^2} = 1$$;$$\\frac{dz}{dx} + \\frac{(-2z)}{x} = 1$$;$$\\therefore \\frac{dz}{dx} - \\frac{2z}{x} = 1$$ (ans);;(iii)With $$\\frac{1}{y^2} = - 2z$$;$$\\frac{dy}{dx} + \\frac{y}{x} = {y}^3   \\equiv  \\frac{dz}{dx} - \\frac{2z}{x} = 1$$;Let $$h(x) = \\int (-\\frac{2}{x})dx = - 2\\ln x = -\\ln x^2$$;$$\\Rightarrow $$ integrating factor, $$e^{h(x)} = e^{-\\ln x^2} = \\frac{1}{x^2}$$ and $$e^{-h(x)} = e^{\\ln x^2} = x^2$$;$$\\therefore$$ General solution is;$$z = e^{-h(x)}[\\int e^{h(x)}(1)dx + c]$$, c = constant;$$ = x^2[\\int \\frac{1}{x^2}dx + c]$$;$$ = x^2[-\\frac{1}{x} + c] = - x + cx^2$$;At $$x = 1$$, $$y = 2$$, $$z = -\\frac{1}{2(2)^2} = -\\frac{1}{8}$$,;$$\\Rightarrow -\\frac{1}{8} = - (1) + c (1)^2  \\Rightarrow  c = \\frac{7}{8}$$;$$\\therefore z = - x + \\frac{7}{8}x^2$$;$$\\equiv -\\frac{1}{2y^2} = - x + \\frac{7}{8}x^2$$;$$ - 4 = - 8xy^2 + 7x^2y^2 = 0$$;$$\\therefore 7x^2y^2 - 8xy^2 + 4 = 0$$ (ans)'),
