('200604003005','$$ x^3 + x = 100 \\equiv x^3 = 100-x $$;Sketch $$ y = x^3 $$ and y = 100 - x;img;;The graphs of $$ y=x^3 $$ and y = 100-x intersect at exactly one point($$ x=\\alpha $$);$$ \\Rightarrow $$ the equation;$$ x^3 = 100-x \\equiv x^3+x = 100 $$;has exactly 1 real root $$ \\alpha $$;;Let $$ f(x) = x^3 + x -100 $$;$$ f(4) = (4)^3 + 4 - 100 = -32 < 0 $$;$$ f(5) = (5)^3 + 5 - 100 = 30 > 0 $$;$$ \\Rightarrow f(x) =0 $$ has a root $$ \\alpha \\in [4,5] $$;;Linear interpolation on [4,5];$$\\begin{align} x_1 \\approx \\frac{(4)|f(5)|+(5)|f(4)|}{|f(5)|+|f(4)|};\\\\ \\frac{(4)|30|+(5)|-32|}{|30|+|-32|} ;\\\\ = 4.516 = 4.5 (1dp)\\end{align}$$;;Let $$ g(x) = \\sqrt[3]{100-x} =(100-x)^\\frac{1}{3}$$;$$ g\'(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} [\\sqrt[3]{100-x}] = -\\frac{1}{3}(100-x)^{-\\frac{2}{3}}$$;$$ |g\'(x_1)| = |-\\frac{1}{3} (100-4.5)^{-\\frac{2}{3}}| = 0.016<1 $$ and;$$ x=g(x) [\\equiv x^3 + x -100 = 0] $$ is smooth in the vicinity of $$ x = x_1 $$ and $$ x = \\alpha $$;$$ \\Rightarrow $$ the iteration $$ x_{n+1} = \\sqrt[3]{100-x_n} $$ should converge from $$ x_1 $$ to $$ \\alpha $$;;Starting with $$ x_1 = 4.516 $$, ;$$ x_2 = \\sqrt[3]{100-x_1} = \\sqrt[3]{100-(4.516)} = 4.5706 = 4.571 (3dp) $$;$$ x_3 = \\sqrt[3]{100-x_2} = \\sqrt[3]{100-(4.571)} = 4.5698 = 4.570 (3dp) $$;$$ f(4.570 + 0.0005) $$;$$ = (4.5705)^3 + (4.5705) - 100 = 0.0458 > 0 $$;$$ f(4.570 - 0.0005) $$;$$ = (4.5695)^3 + (4.5695) - 100 = -0.0178 < 0 $$;$$ \\therefore $$ Correct to 3 decimal places, $$ \\alpha = 4.570$$'),
