(964, 'Compound Angle Identities', 'F', 36, '(i) $$\\sin (A + B) = \\sin A \\cos B + \\cos A \\sin B$$\r;(ii) $$\\sin (A - B) = \\sin A \\cos B - \\cos A \\sin B$$\r;(iii) $$\\cos (A + B) = \\cos A \\cos B  - \\sin A \\sin B$$\r;(iv) $$\\cos (A - B) = \\cos A \\cos B + \\sin A \\sin B$$\r;(v) $$\\tan (A + B) = \\frac{\\tan A + \\tan B}{1 - \\tan A \\tan B}$$\r;(vi) $$\\tan (A - B) = \\frac{\\tan A - \\tan B}{1 + \\tan A \\tan B}$$'),
(965, 'Double angle formulae', 'F', 36, '(i) $$\\sin 2A = 2 \\sin A \\cos A$$\r;(ii) $$\\cos 2A = \\cos^{2} A - \\sin^{2} A$$\r;(iii)$$\\tan 2A = \\frac{2 \\tan A}{1 - \\tan^{2} A}$$'),
(966, 'Half Angle Formulae', 'F', 36, '(i) $$\\sin 2A = \\frac{2 \\tan A}{1 + \\tan^{2} A}$$\r;(ii) $$\\cos 2A = \\frac{1 - \\tan^{2} A}{1 + \\tan^{2} A}$$\r;\r;Replace $$2A$$ with $$x$$ and use $$T$$ for $$\\tan (x/2)$$ '),
(967, 'Factor Formulae', 'F', 36, 'If $$A + B = J$$ and $$A - B = K$$\r;(i) $$\\sin J + \\sin K = 2 \\sin \\frac{J + K}{2} \\cos \\frac{J - K}{2}$$\r;(ii) $$\\sin J - \\sin K = 2 \\cos \\frac{J + K}{2} \\sin \\frac{J - K}{2}$$\r;(iii) $$\\cos J + \\cos K = 2 \\cos \\frac{J + K}{2} \\cos \\frac{J - K}{2}$$\r;(iv) $$\\cos J - \\cos K = - 2 \\sin \\frac{J + K}{2} \\sin \\frac{J - K}{2}$$'),
(968, 'Rcos Function', 'C', 36, 'This method is based upon the fact that combining a sine and a cosine will generate another cos curve with a greater amplitude and which is a number of degrees out of phase with the graph of $$\\cos \\theta$$.\r;\r;This means that it can be written as $$R \\cos (\\theta - \\alpha)$$, where $$R$$ represents the amplitude and $$\\alpha$$ represents the number of degrees the graph is out of phase (to the right).\r;\r;The solution is based upon the expansion of $$\\cos (\\theta - \\alpha)$$.'),
